Car Prices

# Load your libraries
library(mosaic)
library(DT)
library(car)
library(tidyverse)
library(pander)

Background

When buying a car, its important to consider the resale value as well as how long you plan to keep the car youll eventually buy. Linear regression models can help predict resale values based on mileage. To demonstrate this, Ill use a Two Lines Model multi-linear regression to compare the price depreciation of two car models.

Hide Data

A dataset for car prices has been provided for analysis by Brigham Young University - Idaho.

Show Data

The dataset includes observations for 32 models, so well pick the model and trim with the smallest range in observed prices. Ill limit our search to sedans since different car types certainly depreciate at different rates.

Original Data

datatable(CarPrices)

Cleaned Data

The two models with the smallest range in price are the Cavalier LS Sport Sedan 4D and the Malibu Sedan 4D.

Model_Price_Range <- CarPrices %>% 
  select(Make, Model, Trim, Type, Price) %>%
  filter(Type == 'Sedan') %>% 
  group_by(Model, Trim) %>% 
  summarise(range = max(Price) - min(Price)) %>% 
  arrange(range)

datatable(Model_Price_Range, options=list(lengthMenu = c(2,10,30)), extensions="Responsive")
CarPrices2 <- CarPrices %>% 
  select(Price, Mileage, Make, Model, Trim, Type) %>% 
  filter(Trim == 'LS Sport Sedan 4D' | Trim == 'Sedan 4D') %>% 
  filter(Model == 'Cavalier' | Model == 'Malibu') %>% 
  mutate(
    model_trim_id = case_when(
      Model == "Cavalier" & Trim == "LS Sport Sedan 4D" ~ 0,
      Model == "Malibu" & Trim == "Sedan 4D" ~ 1,
      Model == "Cavalier" & Trim == "Sedan 4D" ~ 2,
    )
  )

CarPrices2 <- CarPrices2 %>% 
  filter(model_trim_id != 2) %>% 
  select(Price, Mileage, Make, Model, Trim, Type)

datatable(CarPrices2, options=list(lengthMenu = c(10,30)))

The Model

The mathematical model for this Two-lines model is as follows: \[ \underbrace{Y_i}_{\text{Price}} = \overbrace{\beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_{i1}}_{\text{Mileage}}}^{\text{Cavalier Line}} + \overbrace{\beta_2 \underbrace{X_{i2}}_{\text{1 if Malibu}} + \beta_3 \underbrace{X_{i1} X_{i2}}_{\text{Interaction}}}^{\text{Malibu Adjustments to Line}} + \epsilon_i \] \[ X_{2i} = \left\{\begin{array}{ll} 1 & \text{if it's for the Malibu} \\ 0 & \text{if it's for the Cavalier} \end{array}\right. \]
\[\epsilon_i\sim N(0,\sigma^2)\]

This model breaks down into the following two mathematical models for each car model well be working with:

Vehicle Value of \(X_{i2}\) Resulting Model
Cavalier \(X_{i2} = 0\) \(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)
Malibu \(X_{i2} = 1\) \(Y_i = (\beta_0 + \beta_2) + (\beta_1 + \beta_3) X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)

Well use these resulting models to plot the data later on in the analysis.

Hypothesis

There will be two hypotheses well test in this analysis. ### The Equal y-Intercepts Hypothesis

If the y-intercepts are equal (or if \(\beta_2 =0\)), then the cars have the same average cost when brand new, but if they are not equal (or if \(\beta_2 \neq 0\)) than one car is generally more expensive than the other.

\[ H_0: \beta_2 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal average cost when brand new)} \\ H_a: \beta_2 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal average cost when brand new)} \]

The Equal Slopes Hypothesis

If the slopes are equal, then the cars depreciate at the same rate and so youll lose the same amount of money per mile no matter which car you pick.

\[ H_0: \beta_3 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal rates of depreciation)} \\ H_a: \beta_3 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal rates of depreciation)} \]

Analysis

Test for Equal Slopes

When we conduct a multi-linear regression on this data, we return the following information.

lmout <- lm(Price ~ Mileage + Model + Mileage:Model,
            data = CarPrices2)
summary(lmout) %>% pander
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 15048 414.7 36.29 8.507e-17
Mileage -0.07124 0.02214 -3.217 0.005381
ModelMalibu 3491 592.8 5.889 2.286e-05
Mileage:ModelMalibu -0.03766 0.03163 -1.191 0.2512
Fitting linear model: Price ~ Mileage + Model + Mileage:Model
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
20 381.7 0.9501 0.9407 
coef <- lmout$coefficients
#we'll need this to make lines on our plots

With a p-value of 0.2512, our \(\beta_3\) or Mileage:model_trim_id is not statistically significant. In other words, \(\beta_3 = 0\). Since the other \(\beta\) values are statistically significant we wont have to rerun this model for the slope hypothesis test and can conclude that we have failed to reject the null hypothesis, and that we must assume that the two car models prices depreciate at the same rate.

Test for Equal y-Intercepts

We will need to remove \(\beta_3\) in order to do the y-intercept hypothesis test since \(\beta_3\) was statistically insignificant. All else remaining the same, the new model will be as follows:

Vehicle Value of \(X_{i2}\) Resulting Model
Cavalier \(X_{i2} = 0\) \(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)
Malibu \(X_{i2} = 1\) \(Y_i = (\beta_0 + \beta_2) + (\beta_1) X_{i1} + \epsilon_i\)

Here is the accompanying multi-linear regression for the new model.

lmout2 <- lm(Price ~ Mileage + Model,
            data = CarPrices2)
summary(lmout2) %>% pander
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 15379 311.7 49.34 8.51e-20
Mileage -0.0897 0.01601 -5.604 3.16e-05
ModelMalibu 2815 172.8 16.29 8.273e-12
Fitting linear model: Price ~ Mileage + Model
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
20 386.3 0.9457 0.9393 
coef2 <- lmout2$coefficients

The remaining \(\beta\) values are all significant and since \(\beta_2\) (or model) has a p-value of 8.273e-12 we can conclude that we have sufficient evidence to accept the alternative hypothesis and that the starting prices of the two models are not equal to one another.

Lets visualize what weve found.

palette(c("green","blue"))

plot(Price ~ Mileage,
     data = CarPrices2,
     col = Model,
     main = "Price of Cars by Mileage"
    )

# Add regression line
abline(a=coef2[1], 
       b=coef2[2], 
       col="blue")
abline(a=coef2[1] + coef2[3], 
       b=coef2[2], 
       col="green")

# Add legend:
  legend("topright",
         col = palette(), 
         legend = c("Malibu",
                    "Cavalier"), 
         bty="n", 
         text.col = palette())

As we can see, our above conclusions are correct: the slopes do look approximately equal and the two cars clearly dont have the same price when they are brand new.

Assumptions Tests

Lets check the assumptions. 

# This chunk uses ```{r, fig.height=3} to shrink the heigh of the graphs.
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(lmout2, which=1)
qqPlot(lmout2$residuals)
## [1] 18  8
mtext(side=3,text="Q-Q Plot of Residuals")
plot(lmout2$residuals)
mtext(side=3, text="Residuals vs. Order")

The assumptions have all been meet.

Since the Residuals vs Fitted plot doesnt show a pattern, we can conclude that X and Y have a linear relationship and that error terms are normally distributed with a mean of zero (assumptions one and two respectively).

The Q-Q Plot of Residuals proves that we have a constant variance and that our data is normal (the third assumption).

We can assume that the X values (or mileage) has been measured without error (the fourth assumption).

Lastly, since the Residuals vs.Order plot doesnt show a pattern, we can conclude that the error terms are independent of each other (assumption five).

Conclusion

Since the cars depreciate at the same rate, buyers can purchase either one with the assumption that theyll lose the least amount of money via mileage over either of these two options and (since the relationship between mileage and price is linear) they can safely assume that the depreciation rate will be constant for as long as they have the vehicle.
